            <fr:addr>jms-00I7</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00I7.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Relation">Relation</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>A <html:em><html:strong>(binary) relation</html:strong></html:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> from a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>, written <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R\colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } B]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R\in  \mathrm {Rel}{\mathopen {}\left (A,B\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> is defined to be a subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R\subseteq  A\times  B]]></fr:tex>. We shall typically write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\mathrel {R}b]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (a,b\right )\mathclose {}}\in  R]]></fr:tex>. More generally, a <html:em><html:strong>relation between multiple sets</html:strong></html:em> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (A_i\right )\mathclose {}}_{i\in  I}]]></fr:tex> is defined to be a subset of the cartesian product <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\prod _{i\in  I} A_i]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
